INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2001-06-19 22:27','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','Loma Public Education Fund Operating Committees','Currently over 60 parent volunteers are working within the LPEF. Major summer work will focus on producing the October 6th Gala and Auction, as well as initiating our Pledge Drive. Administrative efforts will focus on creating infrastructure and continuing relationship building within the community and school district.','<p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> EVENT FUNDRAISING COMMITTEES  <p class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:.5in\'><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'>A.</span></b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family: Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span><b>Gala Committee</b> ( <b>Michelle McAuliffe, 353-9080, <a href=\"mailto:Michelle@laseraid.com\">Michelle@laseraid.com</a><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span>& Sandy Whitney, 353-1044, <a href=\"mailto:CasadelSol@yahoo.com\">CasadelSol@yahoo.com</a> </b>) </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">            </span>This committee is responsible for producing the annual Gala event, excluding auction portion </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:.5in\'><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'>B.<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span>Auction Committee (Amy Weingarten, 353-8820, <a href=\"mailto:aweingflo@yahoo.com\">aweingflo@yahoo.com</a> & Cathy Lanagan, 353-8384, <a href=\"mailto:cnlanagan@aol.com\">cnlanagan@aol.com</a> )</span></b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">            </span>This committee will handle all aspects of the auction </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>DIRECT FUNDRAISING COMMITTEE </span></b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family: Verdana\'></span></p> <p class=MsoNormal style=\'text-indent:.5in\'><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'>A.<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span>Pledge Drive (Jean Niemann, 353-5625, <a href=\"mailto:Niemann.six@verizon.net\">Niemann.six@verizon.net</a><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span>) </span></b></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">      </span><span style=\'mso-tab-count:1\'>    </span>Plan and execute annual pledge drive, both Corporate and Individual. </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">      </span><span style=\'mso-tab-count:1\'>    </span><b>B</b>.<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span>Endowment Fund </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">      </span><span style=\'mso-tab-count:1\'>    </span>Define structure, research legal requirements, implement campaign and manage fund. </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">      </span><span style=\'mso-tab-count:1\'>    </span><b>C.</b><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span><b>Grant Writing (Celia Maddox, 353-5973, <a href=\"mailto:Celia2@attglobal.net\">Celia2@attglobal.net</a>) </b></span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">      </span><span style=\'mso-tab-count:1\'>    </span>Perform needs analysis, research availability and write grants to meet fund/school district objectives. </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>FINANCE COMMITTEE/TREASURER (Gerald O&#8217;Regan, 353-8313, </span></b></p> <p class=MsoNormal style=\'text-indent:.5in\'><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'><a href=\"mailto:Grgn@chevron.com\">Grgn@chevron.com</a>)</span></b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>ADMINISTRATIVE, LIAISON AND FUNDING COMMITTEE </span></b></p> <p class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:.5in\'><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'>(Lydia Dobyns, 353-2433, <a href=\"mailto:Lydia@Dobyns.com\">Lydia@Dobyns.com</a>, Pat McGrath, 353-2144, <a href=\"mailto:pkmcgrath@aol.com\">pkmcgrath@aol.com</a>, Julie Gouldsbury, 353-8223, <a href=\"mailto:Julie@gouldsberry.com\">Julie@gouldsberry.com</a>)</span></b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">      </span><span style=\'mso-tab-count:1\'>    </span>In general this committee will manage all activities associated with getting LPEF funds to the district </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>PR/COMMUNICATION COMMITTEE<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </span>(Joan Hoffman, 353-5088, <a href=\"mailto:JMH4@inreach.com\">JMH4@inreach.com</a>)</span></b></p> <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=\'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'> </span></b></p> <p class=MsoBodyText2>If you are willing to work with us over the summer, please contact Pat McGrath, Julie Gouldsbury or Lydia Dobyns</p> <p class=MsoNormal><span style=\'font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\'> </span></p> <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=\'font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:Verdana\'>Thank you!',NULL,'barry','barry@dobyns.com',NULL,1,559,'2001-06-19 22:27:49',20071114080245,'2001-06-19 22:27:49');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2001-08-28 22:20','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','2001-2002 Grants Announced','LPEF Announces First Round of Grants for the Loma Prieta School District','<DIV class=Section1>        <B>LPEF Announces First Round of Grants for the Loma Prieta School     District</B>      <P class=MsoNormal>   Following months of exploring ways to help improve   the educational experience for students in the Loma Prieta Joint Union School   District, the Loma Public Education Fund (LPEF) is pleased to announce its   first round of grants totaling $100,000. Working closely with Superintendent   and Principal Mary Ellen Lewis, Principal Lorrie Wernick, and surveying teachers   throughout the district, the District has created three new programs and   selected three programs to expand for the 2001 school year. LPEF anticipates   funding additional programs once the pledge drive (have you mailed your check   back?) and the October 6th fundraising Gala (call 353-9970 for   tickets) are concluded.   <P class=MsoNormal>   The initial 2001- 2002 grants are:   <P class=MsoNormal>    <SPAN       style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol; text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>·<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>          </SPAN></SPAN><B style=\'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\'><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>District Volunteer Training and Scheduling   Coordinator</SPAN></B><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>:<SPAN style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </SPAN>This   new position will allow the recruitment and training of volunteers throughout   the district to assist in classrooms as well as help teachers with administrative   projects.<SPAN style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </SPAN>Will coordinate volunteers   to assure coverage when needed allowing the District to better utilize volunteers   and save staffing costs.</SPAN>   <P class=MsoTitle align=left style=\'margin-left:.5in;text-align:left; text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l10 level1 lfo12;tab-stops:list .5in left 3.0in\'>   <SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol; text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>·<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>          </SPAN></SPAN><B style=\'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\'><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>Loma Reading   Intervention</SPAN></B><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>: Last year this was a half time position (paid for   by Federal funds), and by expanding to a fulltime program we can extend the   reading intervention to all First through Fifth graders. The program will   provide reading intervention assistance to students and train classroom teachers   to employ reading improvement techniques within the classroom. Started by   teacher Helga Dinning as a pilot project last year using Federal funds, and   buoyed by great results and feedback from students and parents, the grant   from LPEF will enable this to become a fulltime program. </SPAN>   <P class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l10 level1 lfo12;tab-stops:list .5in\'>   <SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol; text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>·<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>          </SPAN></SPAN><B style=\'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\'>Loma Math   Intervention</B>:<SPAN style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </SPAN>This new math   intervention program similar to the reading program, for second through fifth   grades. A part-time specialist will be hired to provide hands-on math skills.   <P class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l0 level1 lfo10;tab-stops:list .5in\'>   <SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol; text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>·<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>          </SPAN></SPAN><B>C.T. English Math Club</B>. A new after-school   math club will be offered for CT English students, as a companion program   to the very successful Homework Club sponsored by the Home and School Club.   <P class=MsoTitle align=left style=\'margin-left:.5in;text-align:left; text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l10 level1 lfo12;tab-stops:list .5in left 3.0in\'>   <SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol; text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>·<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>          </SPAN></SPAN><B style=\'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\'><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>Expansion of C.T. Library and Computer Lab   time</SPAN></B><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>:<SPAN style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </SPAN>Currently   open three days a week during school   hours.<SPAN style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </SPAN>This funding would allow   the library and computer lab to be open before, during and after school five   days per week. </SPAN>   <P class=MsoTitle align=left style=\'margin-left:.5in;text-align:left; text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l10 level1 lfo12;tab-stops:list .5in left 3.0in\'>   <SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol; text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>·<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>          </SPAN></SPAN><B style=\'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\'><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>C.T English Counseling   Services</SPAN></B><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none; text-underline:none\'>:<SPAN style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">  </SPAN>Counseling   services are currently available two days a week and by expanding to a third   day, Dr. Wernick feels we will be able to offer vital services to all middle   school students who desire support.</SPAN>   <P class=MsoNormal>   Asked to comment on the grants being awarded, Superintendent and Principal   Mary Ellen Lewis said &#8220;I have been meeting with the Loma teaching staff   and can tell you that we are thrilled to be able to make this additional,   serious commitment to reading and math intervention programs. As a teaching   staff we are genuinely excited about the possibilities of tackling and conquering   reading challenges because we know that if we ensure every student can read   at or above grade level each student has a much greater chance of being   successful in school. We are especially eager to invest in a volunteer training   and scheduling coordinator. This position will make an incredible difference   to the students and teachers by helping us better utilize the fantastic talent   among the many parent volunteers. We are so grateful to this partnership   with our parents enabled by the Education Fund. Thank you parents!&#8221;   <P class=MsoNormal>     &#8220;As principal   of the middle school,&#8221; Dr. Lorrie Wernick added, &#8220;I am so appreciative   of the possibilities of being able to offer additional counseling services,   an after school program for math, and to allow students access to our computer   lab, and library every school day before during and after school. We feel   very fortunate to have the support of our community and look forward to creating   additional programs to benefit the CT English students.&#8221;   <P class=MsoNormal>   <SPAN style=\'font-size: 12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>The   program grants are made possible by generous financial contributions by parents,   the annual benefit fund raising gala to be held on October 6th, 2001   and corporate underwriters. Founded earlier this year, the purpose of LPEF   is to raise significant money to preserve and enhance the District&#8217;s   ability to offer outstanding educational programs. LPEF operates as a separate   arm of the Loma Prieta Community Foundation with its own executive committee.   The LPEF Executive Steering Committee received funding requests for twelve   programs from the District. After reviewing the requests, six initial programs   were nominated and approved. Each grant includes written objectives, measurement   criteria, financial requirements and reporting   schedules.</SPAN><SPAN style=\'text-decoration: none;text-underline:none\'>   </SPAN><SPAN style=\'font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt;text-decoration:none;text-underline:none\'>It is a LPEF goal to work   closely with the District, the Home and School Clubs, and School Site Councils   to develop coordinated funding strategies that best benefit our   students.',NULL,'barry','barry@dobyns.com',NULL,1,560,'2001-08-28 22:20:37',20071115023820,'2001-08-28 22:20:37');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2001-06-15 11:52','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','2001-2002 Funding Priorities',' We believe strong teacher support and involvement is\r\n  vital to Loma Public Education Fund&#146;s success. We want to be ready with\r\n  new programs at the beginning of the 2001-2002 year. We anticipate reaching\r\n  our fundraising target by the end of October. So, what are the best ways\r\n  to utilize $100,000 next year to enhance the educational experience for our\r\n  students? ','  <P>\r\n  <BR clear=ALL>\r\n<SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>&nbsp;We&#146;ve\r\n  heard from parents, and potential corporate donors, that the more specific\r\n  our program goals are the easier it will be to exceed our $100,000. We are\r\n  preparing letters that will go to parents in the next few weeks asking for\r\n  their financial support by participating in our first annual pledge drive.\r\n  Additionally a volunteer team will phone parents as a follow-up to the letter\r\n  (yes, during the summer!). </SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:.25in\'>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>Our preliminary thoughts for 2001-2002 funding center\r\n  around three themes:</SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;\r\ntab-stops:list 1.0in\'>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;\r\n\r\nmso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>1.<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n  </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>There is strong support in the parent community for\r\n  core academic programs that benefit most students.</SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;\r\ntab-stops:list 1.0in\'>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;\r\n\r\nmso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>2.<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n  </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>A desire to develop high standards for every student\r\n  and closing the &#147;achievement gap&#148; between various groups of students\r\n  </SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;\r\ntab-stops:list 1.0in\'>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;\r\n\r\nmso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>3.<SPAN style=\'font:7.0pt \"Times New Roman\"\'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n  </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>Working with the District to ensure current programs\r\n  in developmental PE, the Arts, Library services and technology are maintained\r\n  (and possibly enhanced).</SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>&nbsp;Since\r\n  this is our first funding cycle (both raising and disbursing money), we&#146;re\r\n  definitely in learning mode! Next year we anticipate fielding parent and\r\n  teacher surveys to help assess the effectiveness of our first slate of programs\r\n  funded and to help us identify priorities and opportunities for the 2002-2003\r\n  year.</SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>&nbsp;Here\r\n  are the funding guidelines LPEF has adopted. Ideally every program funded\r\n  by LPEF will meet all the following criteria </SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;\r\n\r\nfont-family:Verdana\'>&nbsp;</SPAN>\r\n  <UL style=\'margin-top:0in\' type=disc>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>Promotes\r\n      excellence </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>Is\r\n      meaningful to all targeted students </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>Enough\r\n      is being spent to make the program worthwhile </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>It\'s\r\n      measurable </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>Has\r\n      long term development benefits </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>Helps\r\n      support district goals </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>Promotes\r\n      a well-rounded student</SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>There\r\n      are adequate district and/or site personnel resources and commitments to\r\n      support the program </SPAN>\r\n    <LI class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo5;tab-stops:list .5in\'>\r\n      <SPAN style=\'font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Verdana\'>There\r\n      are limited or no alternative resources to support the\r\n      program</SPAN>\r\n  </UL>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal style=\'margin-left:.25in\'>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-family:Verdana\'>&nbsp;</SPAN>\r\n  <P class=MsoNormal>\r\n  <SPAN style=\'font-family:Verdana\'>&nbsp;</SPAN>\r\n</DIV>\r\n',NULL,'barry','barry@dobyns.com',NULL,1,481,'2001-06-15 11:52:35',20071115143928,'2001-06-15 11:52:35');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-09-17 01:00','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','LPEF Grants Support Every Student','As community members and parents, each of us has been asked to contribute money and time to LPEF.  Often parents ask, \"How will my child benefit?\" This important question is a primary consideration for LPEF members as we work with the District to determine funding priorities.  Our goal is to make program awards that help all students better reach their full potential.  ','The District (the Board of Trustees, Administrators and Staff) identify program opportunities and develop specific grant requests for LPEF. LPEF encourages the district to develop two kinds of programs: those that directly benefit all students as well as small group intervention programs which indirectly support all students through a \"ripple effect.\" \n\nReading Recovery (RR) is an example of a small group intervention program that has started an enormous \"ripple\".  While only 12-20, first graders directly participate in this program annually; every first grader is assessed to identify those who would most benefit from Reading Recovery. These assessments provide valuable teaching insights for the first grade teachers. As RR students progress the overall classroom reading level increases, allowing teachers to teach at a more advanced curriculum level.  This full class \"ripple\" effect has carried over into the second grade this year. As a result, this \'learning readiness\' will increase every year that RR is offered.  Teachers at CTE are enthusiastic supporters of LPEF\'s investment in RR. \n\nGiven LPEF\'s long-term vision and district-wide mission we are confident that our commitment to RR will fundamentally improve the quality of education for every student from last year onward. Another \"positive ripple\" according to Superintendent and Principal Mary Ellen Lewis Johnson are the staff development benefits RR techniques provide. As teaching concepts are shared and new strategies and assessments for working with children in the areas of reading, writing, and spelling are introduced, the entire staff becomes more effective.  \n\nThe other types of grants that LPEF strongly endorses are school-wide programs. Last year we funded school-wide Reading Enrichment at CTE.  Every teacher was given training and materials and assigned a group of students, arranged by reading level. The goal was to help the groups improve reading comprehension. This year LPEF has expanded the award to include a school wide math component.  We also expect to fund expanded counseling services at both schools.  Ms. Lewis-Johnson noted that having adequate counseling services helps improve the \"climate\" of both schools. Benefits of student counseling go well beyond the individual student receiving services-it tends to improve classroom and schoolyard interactions.  \n\nOther programs the district has asked LPEF to fund include purchasing sets of classroom texts, optional 7th period extra curriculum programs at CTE which may include writing, music, and open gym days; and a computer/technology staff person to work directly with Loma teachers to provide computer skills support.  IHS has requested funding for computer equipment and a reading remediation program to provide staff and parent development in teaching reading skills and identifying reading problems.\n\nSo the next time you hear about an LPEF-funded program, please know that each program award has met this simple criteria: spending money on this program can be shown to help every student either directly or indirectly. Our goal is to enhance the educational experience for all children in our District.  With your continued support LPEF can achieve this wonderful vision.\n ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com',NULL,1,587,'2002-09-17 01:00:47',20071114211342,'2002-09-17 01:00:47');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-08-03 18:49','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','CT Students Benefit From Reading Skills Grant','Veteran CT English teachers Shelby Matlock, Kris Denues, and Melinda Chapin had an ongoing question during their years as language arts instructors.  How do you address the individual needs of students in reading, when students of all reading levels are typically mixed in classes? How do you identify their needs and ensure that no student will fall through the cracks?   \r\n','With the support of the administration and the school board, as well as a grant from LPEF for training, books, and other materials, the CT English Reading Program was instituted in Fall, 2002 to address these questions.  \r\n\r\nMs. Denues, Ms. Matlock, and Ms. Chapin, along with many other CT teachers, attended seminars and workshops geared towards enhancing reading skills, and then developed a program specifically addressing the needs of students at CTE  This is an exciting program, which Ms. Denues noted marked a complete change in the way reading has been taught at CTE  All CTE classroom teachers, as well as Principal Lorrie Wernick and Resource Teacher Carolyn Schmidt, teach two, 1-hour Reading Skills classes each week.  Ms. Denues, Matlock, and Chapin trained the CTE staff and with Principal Wernick continue to develop and review lesson plans with teachers.  The emphasis is on reading across the curriculum, which is geared toward improved reading in all classes.\r\n\r\nMs. Chapin has a goal for every single student to be reading and comprehending well.  No student should drop through the cracks and at the same time, we want to challenge every reader. To achieve this goal, CTE teachers use specific techniques, such as Socratic questioning.  There is no right answer to a Socratic question, but a student has to support his or her response with evidence from the text.  The students also appear more comfortable and willing to participate in the skill-based groups (see insert) than in the regular classroom setting.\r\n\r\nAs Ms. Denues noted, the Reading Program may be one of the last chances for the students to really get formal reading instruction.  One way to gauge its success is if students can walk off this campus in June not feeling threatened by a piece of nonfiction writing, and if they feel comfortable picking up a book for fun.  The effort and enthusiasm put into this program by Ms. Denues, Chapin, and Matlock, as well as the staff at CTE, cannot easily be put into words.  LPEF has been pleased to support this program which helps our middle school children be better readers, as well as more successful and prepared for the years ahead.\r\n\r\nThe Reading Program at CTE\r\n·	Students in each grade are placed in one of four skill-based groups based on SAT-9 Total Reading score\r\n·	Periodic assessment using Reading Concepts and STAR Reading Tests are performed for well-rounded assessments \r\n·	Skill-based groups are fluid- a student can move to different group as reading skills improve\r\n·	Program effectiveness will be evaluated at the end of the year\r\n·	Skill-based groups work on target areas (e.g., reading accuracy, comprehension, critical thinking) depending on need\r\n     ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,512,'2002-08-03 18:49:46',20070915150931,'2002-08-03 18:49:46');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-08-03 17:59','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','LPEF Grant helps Loma Elementary Adopt Reading Recovery Program in 2001','When it came to choosing a reading intervention program at Loma, Principal/Superintendent Mary Ellen Lewis and the teachers at Loma knew what they wanted.  Second grade teachers Helga Dinning and Laurie Brandt approached Ms. Lewis about implementing Reading Recovery (RR) for the 2001-2002 school year. According to Ms. Brandt, Reading Recovery (RR) is known among teachers as the most successful reading intervention program in English-speaking countries.  \r\n\r\n','Ms. Dinning described RR as a teacher-based, not materials-based, program, which requires an intense training year as RR providers.  They attended a 5-day training in August and continue to train one night a week for 4 hours in Santa Cruz.  Three times a year, they are observed and evaluated by their peers and their RR teacher leader, Bonnie Thurston.  She evaluates their administration of a RR session through a one-way mirror (called Behind the Glass).  Ms.Thurston also reviews the work and progress of LP students receiving RR intervention, and provides support and strategies with Ms. Dinning and Brandt to augment the training experience and provide the best services for the children.  Laurie Brandt commented that using Reading Recovery techniques has lifted my own teaching, and she finds herself using RR strategies with her 2nd graders.\r\n\r\nMs. Brandt reported that RR looks at each child individually by asking the question, What specifically does this child need to learn today, tomorrow, this minute?   In a typical RR session, a child will choose books he or she is familiar with to read in session, participate in a daily writing task, and work on breaking down the sounds in words.  The child also has nightly reading and writing homework to reinforce skills and strategies taught that day. Parents are invited to observe a lesson with their child.  \r\n\r\nMs. Dinning and Brandt communicate frequently with the kindergarten and first grade teachers to conference and assess the RR students reading and writing progress in the classroom.  RR targets the needs of the highest at-risk readers in first grade.  Children who do not make significant progress in RR can be referred for additional assessments early on, which will help identify children with learning disabilities before a cycle of failure begins.\r\n\r\nMs. Dinning stressed the importance of building on what strategies a child already has; building on what they already know, while Ms. Brandt noted that having children be independent readers in the classroom is a key goal.  They are passionate about this program and will assess these children for five years after program completion to evaluate the effectiveness of this intervention.  More information about RR can be found on their website (www.readingrecovery.org).    \r\n\r\nReading Recovery Facts\r\n·	Developed by Dr. Marie M. Clay in New Zealand\r\n·	An intervention program, not remediation (works with students before gaps in learning develop)\r\n·	Over 1 million children will be served by RR this year\r\n·	81% of students who completed RR read within the average range of their class by the end of first grade\r\n·	Data-collection from every RR site in the U.S. is sent to The National Center for Reading Recovery at Ohio State University to support research and evaluation of RR \r\n\r\nReading Recovery at Loma Prieta\r\n·	18 1st graders initially assessed\r\n·	16 children will have participated by the end of the year\r\n·	Each student receives individual intervention 30 minutes/session, 5 days/week for 16 to 20 weeks\r\n·	Of the 8 recent graduates, all were initially reading significantly below grade level- at program completion, all were reading at or beyond 1st grade standards\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  \r\n ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,592,'2002-08-03 17:59:14',20071008030921,'2002-08-03 17:59:14');
