INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-08-03 18:30','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','LPEF Incorporated as Loma Public Education Fund','When LPEF was formed in February 2001, we approached the Loma Prieta Community Foundation (LPCF) and asked for permission to operate under its legal structure. ','When LPEF was formed in February 2001, we approached the Loma Prieta Community Foundation (LPCF) and asked for permission to operate under its legal structure. The agreement with LPCF was for one year, so that we could focus on raising money for the 01-02 school year, through the Gala and Pledge Drive. \n\nWe are grateful to LPCF for their initial sponsorship. Contacting other educational foundations helped us shape the organizational structure for LPEF. Ultimately, for the cleanest management of funds, the LPEF Executive Steering Committee felt that we should be our own entity and voted in December 2001 to incorporate as a new, separate non-profit corporation. \n\nArticles of incorporation and applications for non-profit designation were completed in early 2002. As of July 1, 2002 LPEF received 501 (c) 3, non-profit status.   ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com',NULL,1,740,'2002-08-03 18:30:00',20071113001303,'2002-08-03 18:30:00');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-08-03 18:34','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','Loma Public Education Fund Philosophy and Mission','LPEF has structured itself to focus on fund-raising and awarding specific grants for programs administered by teachers and district staff.\n','Our District is small and enrollment is declining. If you&#8217;re following the news, you know that the State of California is in its worst financial predicament in years. School funding will be decreasing. If we want to retain excellent teachers, maintain current programs and foster innovation, we must bring new revenues into our schools. This is the primary focus for LPEF. \n\nLPEF has structured itself to focus on fund-raising and awarding specific grants for programs administered by teachers and district staff (like Reading Recovery). We do not seek grants from external organizations for LPEF per se, because we do not want to operate programs. We feel that it is the responsibility of the school board, administrators and teachers to determine educational policy, and to select and implement educational programs. We are pleased with the working relationships we&#8217;ve developed with District Staff. Raising money, is a HUGE job. Helping the District develop measurement criteria for each grant is another HUGE job. Recruiting and managing an all-volunteer organization is a HUGE job, well, you get the idea. We&#8217;re at our limit! \n\nLPEF works with the District to locate outside funding from local corporations and foundations to help share the costs of maintaining programs. Recently LPEF volunteers helped prepare a grant that the District submitted to Applied Materials for $69,500 to continue Reading Recovery. LPEF plans to help the District identify and submit grant proposals to help fund other programs initially paid for by LPEF grants.\n\nLPEF is a funding incubator for innovation. We want to help establish programs and then work with the District to find ways to become financially responsible for the ongoing program costs. We do not anticipate providing permanent funding for any program. By limiting ongoing funding for programs, we will be able to assist the District in piloting innovative programs year after year.  \n\n\n ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com',NULL,1,549,'2002-08-03 18:34:13',20071113001235,'2002-08-03 18:34:13');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-08-03 18:58','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','Math Club and Counseling Services Aid CT students','LPEF Funding Pays for After-School Math and Counseling Services at CT English','The After School Math Club is held two to four times a week with Cece Anderson at the helm.  Substitute teacher Nick Hoffman also works with students on afternoons when he is available.  One 8th grade participant commented, Ms. Anderson makes it easier for tests because she has a study session before tests, while another 8th grader offered, It helps you get your homework done-with help!  The LPEF also funds one day per week of counseling services for CTE students.',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,678,'2002-08-03 18:58:22',20070915150940,'2002-08-03 18:58:22');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2002-08-03 19:01','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','Pilot Math Intervention Program Offered at Loma','New math intervention program serves second through fifth graders.','Linda Smith taught 5th graders for four years, as well as two years at the middle school level, in the mid-70s, but the kindergarten classroom is where she has worked since then.  This year, however, when a half-time position arose to get the LPEF-funded Math Intervention (MI) program off and running, it proved to be a good match for Ms. Smith and Loma Prieta. She noted, I am absolutely loving itINSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9383689','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Why do we need a special fundraising campaign?','We need to raise money, on an annual basis, to maintain excellent educational programs for our children. ','We need to raise money, on an annual basis, to maintain excellent educational programs for our children.  Unfortunately, maintaining smaller class sizes, a robust middle school curriculum and providing means to future innovation is tied to annual fundraising since the revenues provided by the State are simply not enough to pay for broad educational programs. The district will be forced to make dramatic cuts in staffing and programs next school year if we do not reach our KEEP campaign goal.\r\n\r\nThis budget situation has been developing over the last several years and is the result of dramatic increases in mandated program costs, such as Special Education, (over which the district has no control), and declining enrollment. Although the district has tapped reserves in past years to pay for smaller class sizes and programs, as of last year there are no more reserves available to augment the revenue from the state. Consequently 90% of the districts unrestricted expenditures are spent on salaries and benefits. Without a successful KEEP campaign 2 teaching positions will be eliminated, and numerous programs must be eliminated or reduced (such as 50% of CT Elective classes, Developmental PE, Library Services, Student Counseling and MVP).\r\n',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,293,'2005-03-12 20:21:02',20070702183819,'2005-03-12 20:21:02');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9512474','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','How much money is needed?','Superintendent Henry Castaniada has identified $280,000 to $314,000 as the campaign target. If successful, the following priority list of jobs and programs will be funded in this order','Superintendent Henry Castaniada has identified $280,000 to $314,000 as the campaign target. If successful, the following priority list of jobs and programs will be funded in this order:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>2 Teaching positions saved.  This will allow the district to maintain a variety of elective offerings at CTE, maintain smaller class sizes in Grades 4-8, provide instruction, at the middle school in Technology. $150,000\r\n<li>Maintain Library Services at both schools, $22,000\r\n<li>Developmental PE, $53,000\r\n<li>Student counseling at both schools, $12,000\r\n<li>MVP (Music, Visual and Performing Arts) at Loma, $15,000\r\n<li>Technology updates and upgrades for K-8 ($8,000)\r\n<li>New Loma Science Activity Lab Created ($20,000)\r\n<li>Foreign Language: 4th-5th grades ($10,000)\r\n<li>New Music Classes ($14,000)\r\n<li>New K-8 Library System ($10,000)\r\n</ol>',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,268,'2005-03-12 20:20:52',20070928063050,'2005-03-12 20:20:52');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9584590','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What are the suggested donations per family?','The suggested family contributions are the same as last year: $600 for one child and $900 for more than one child. However, assuming the same percentage of families participate this year, every family needs to approach this year with a new mission: combine your KEEP cash contribution with supporting other fundraising activities to reach a total contribution per family of $1,200 for one child and $1,800 for more than one child. ','The suggested family contributions are the same as last year: $600 for one child and $900 for more than one child. However, assuming the same percentage of families participate this year, every family needs to approach this year with a new mission: combine your KEEP cash contribution with supporting other fundraising activities to reach a total contribution per family of $1,200 for one child and $1,800 for more than one child. ',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,193,'2005-03-12 20:19:04',20070504115030,'2005-03-12 20:19:04');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9635305','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Is my KEEP contribution tax deductible?','Yes! LPEF is a non-profit 501(c)3 corporation and all contributions are 100% tax deductible.','Yes! LPEF is a non-profit 501(c)3 corporation and all contributions are 100% tax deductible.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,259,'2005-03-12 20:18:55',20071116111851,'2005-03-12 20:18:55');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2003-01-21 23:43','Y',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','3','2003 Governing Board Elected and Executive Steering Committee Appointed','The LPEF Governing Board for 2003 was elected at the annual meeting, held on January 13, 2003.','Re-elected Governing Board members are Julie Gouldsberry, Celia Maddox, Angela Patterson and Peggy Johnson. Continuing their multi-year terms on the Governing Board  are Adriana Chiocchi, Lydia Dobyns, Pat McGrath and Linda Sullivan. Newly elected Governing Board members are Suzy Kilby, Leslie O\'Malley and Sherrie Starkie. Executive Steering Committee (ESC) members were appointed by the Govering Board. ESC members for 2003 are: Lydia Dobyns, Pat McGrath, Linda Sullivan, Julie Gouldsberry, Celia Maddox, Angela Patterson, Suzy Kilby, Leslie O\'Malley and Sherrie Starkie. ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com',NULL,1,1496,'2003-01-21 23:43:18',20071113140510,'2003-01-21 23:43:18');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-09-06 18:35','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','Reading Recovery 2004 Program Award','LPEF is pleased to provide partial funding for the highly successful Reading Recovery program, now in its fourth year in the district.','The Reading Recovery program at Loma Prieta is administered by teachers Laurie Brandt and Helga Dinning. \r\n<A HREF=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/2004-05 Reading Recovery.pdf\\\">Reading Recovery Program Award</a>',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,243,'2004-09-06 18:35:01',20071009014418,'2004-09-06 18:35:01');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-09-03 10:53','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','2','2004 Program Award Grants Largest Ever for LPEF','At the District\\\'s request, LPEF has committed over $100,000 in new grants for the 2004-05 school year.','By awarding early, LPEF helped the District retain all CT English teachers and save elective offerings at the middle school. Additionally, LPEF has committed to partial financial support for the Reading Recovery program, student counseling and technology upgrades.\r\n\r\nWe need to do more! Principal Diana Hallock, Superintendent Henry Castaniada and teachers have asked LPEF to fix a critical technology problem (the computer lab at Loma Prieta Elementary has incompatible computers, making it impossible for a whole class to use the same software); pay for the development of a Technology Curriculum for students and teaching staff; and provide funding for after-school enrichment at CT and Loma (such as continuing the Math Club with Ms. Anderson). We can do more with your help.\r\n\r\nOur goal is to raise $120,000 from the annual pledge drive and the October 2nd, 2004 Gala and Auction. With your help we will meet this goal.\r\n\r\nLPEF is asking every family in our district to help do whatever it takes to save and enhance our excellent local schools.  \r\n\r\n<A HREF=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/program awards letter 04-05.pdf\\\">Program Awards Letter</a>',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,308,'2004-09-03 10:53:15',20071029050504,'2004-09-03 10:53:15');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-09-06 18:36','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','Student Counseling Program Grant Award','LPEF helps provide much needed student counseling for both Loma Prieta and CT English students.','This is the fourth year that LPEF has helped fund student counseling.\r\n<A HREF=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/2004-05 Counseling.pdf\\\">Counseling Program Award</a>',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,256,'2004-09-06 18:36:25',20070529065344,'2004-09-06 18:36:25');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-09-06 18:38','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','CT Elective Classes Saved by LPEF Grant','At the request of the District, LPEF awarded a $40,000 program grant in the Spring of 2003 in order to retain current CT English teachers and offer additional elective offerings at the middle school.','This LPEF grant helped make possible the addition of zero period classes and new elective offerings for 7th and 8th grade students.\r\n<a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/CT Electives 04-05.pdf\\\">CT Electives Program Award</a>',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,245,'2004-09-06 18:38:36',20070531134234,'2004-09-06 18:38:36');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-09-06 18:41','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','Loma Prieta Computer Lab Upgraded','Thanks to a LPEF program grant, all classes at Loma will now be able to utilize the computer lab with enough standardized computers equipped with the same software. ','Additionally, this technology grant will help all teachers better communicate and prepare by the purchase of district-wide software licenses.  \r\n<a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/computer upgrades 04-05.pdf\\\">Computer Upgrade Program Award</a>',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,633,'2004-09-06 18:41:30',20070820113745,'2004-09-06 18:41:30');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-10-10 15:53','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','2','One Enchanted Evening Sets a New Record','Combine a sell-out crowd with the efforts of 200 parent and student volunteers, along with the generosity of 300 donors who contributed 400 auction items and you have one truly enchanted evening!','The LPEF Gala held on Oct. 2nd netted $52,000 for critical programs for Loma Prieta and CT English schools. The event, held at Maison du Lac, featured wine tasting, music by the South Bay Stompers, silent auctions and finished with a wonderful dinner, spirited bidding on 5 live auctions, many sponsored by local realtors, and dancing to the music of the Lou DeLuca Band.  Revelers bid on items ranging from student class projects to stunning pieces of art and jewelry, merchandise and wine. \r\n\r\nThanks to sustained extraordinary community support, LPEF has granted over $195,000 in Program Awards to the District since we were founded in 2001. Children in our schools have benefited from programs in math, literacy, after-school enrichment, student counseling and library services funded by LPEF. Last year alone, we raised $95,000; and over 96% of those funds were available for grants. LPEF conducts two major fundraising efforts, the annual Gala and a community pledge drive. Preliminary contributions to the pledge drive are $40,000, which means LPEF is very close to meeting its annual goal. If you would like to make a donation, please visit www.lpef.org for a donation form.\r\n\r\nIn 2001 we knew the need for LPEF existed, and we hoped that we could engage the school administration, teachers and parents in a dialog about critical funding. Frankly, our dream was that we could establish LPEF as a support system for our tiny school district, build a track record that would instill confidence in our organization and, finally, be ready to help ensure strong local public schools remained here on the mountain. We knew we could not expect anyone in Sacramento or Washington to help our district match programs and services found in neighboring districts. We knew that our community would need to step up to help our children receive the most excellent education available.\r\n\r\nFour years later we say from the bottoms of our hearts: THANK YOU to everyone who has helped make our vision a reality. One Enchanted Evening was a smashing success because of the goodness of people. Parents. Neighbors. Friends. Relatives. Merchants. People who have reason to care about our kids and people who have no reason to care other than a commitment to education. We have strived to build trust and confidence in LPEF that money given will be accounted for. \r\n\r\nAt the Districts request, LPEF has committed over $100,000 in new grants for the 2004-2005 school year. By awarding early, LPEF helped the District retain all C.T. English teachers and save elective offerings at the middle school. Additionally, LPEF has committed to partial financial support for the Reading Recovery Program, student counseling and technology upgrades. We are currently talking with the district about other critical funding needs for programs designed to support student achievement.\r\n ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,290,'2004-10-10 15:53:01',20071028160146,'2004-10-10 15:53:01');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('2004-10-10 15:58','N',NULL,'nat.webfountain.com','6','Where Does the Money Go?','At the Districts request, LPEF has committed over $100,000 in new grants for the 2004-2005 school year.','By awarding early, LPEF helped the District retain all C.T. English teachers and save elective offerings at the middle school. Additionally, LPEF has committed to partial financial support for the Reading Recovery Program, student counseling and technology upgrades. \r\n\r\nFundraising is a never-ending challenge.  The magnitude of time, energy and effort to produce the Gala is enormous.  Over 200 parents and community members volunteered time to help produce this event, well over 300 donors contributed 400 items to the auction and 375 attendees make this sold out event truly an evening to remember. All this for a district with less than 600 students.\r\n\r\nWe need to do more! Superintendent Henry Castaniada, Principal Diana Hallock, and teachers have asked LPEF to fix a critical technology problem and provide funding for after-school enrichment at C.T. and Loma.\r\n\r\nWe appreciate every donation whether it is time, money or an item for the auction.  We are especially grateful to Patti and Bill Hughes for the use of their lovely gardens. The gifts of time and classroom projects created by teachers, room parents and students are indeed treasures. We could not hold the Gala without the support of parents, community members and merchants.\r\n\r\nYou might ask, Why do all those people do it?  As volunteers of LPEF we ask ourselves this question often.  And from August 1st until October 15th we ask it hourly!  We can assure you no one volunteers because they enjoy asking friends, neighbors and merchants for money and donations.  So, why?  We believe in our children.  We want their futures to be filled with dreams and aspirationsfor themselves and for others.  We volunteer because we have tremendous trust in our teachers and administrators.  And we have unwavering faith that our community will continue to support us in this mission.\r\n ',NULL,'lydia','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,1370,'2004-10-10 15:58:54',20070602132848,'2004-10-10 15:58:54');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9743573','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What if our family isnt able to donate the suggested amount?','Whats important is that every family contributes to the campaign. Other districts achieve their goals by the mixture of families, some who give less than the suggested amounts, some give more and the rest of the families give what is suggested. Parents will make the campaign a success; were asking','Whats important is that every family contributes to the campaign. Other districts achieve their goals by the mixture of families, some who give less than the suggested amounts, some give more and the rest of the families give what is suggested. Parents will make the campaign a success; were asking every family to give what they can. For people making the minimum donation of $600, they may pay half now and the balance will be charged to a credit card in June 1, 2006.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,270,'2005-03-12 20:17:43',20071116150014,'2005-03-12 20:17:43');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9850770','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What do other local Education Foundations suggest as donations?','Here\\\'s the suggested donations from comparable districts in the bay area:','Here\\\'s the suggested donations from comparable districts in the bay area:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Los Gatos- $600 (1 child); $900 (2 or more children) \r\n<li>Saratoga - $700 (1 child); $1400 (2 children); $2100 (3+ children) \r\n<li>Los Altos - $700 (1 child); $1400 (2 children); $2100 (3+ children)\r\n<li>Menlo Park/ Atherton - $500 (1 child); $1000 (2 children); $1500 (3+ children)\r\n<li>Mill Valley - $500 (1 child); $1000 (2 children); $1500 (3+ children)\r\n<li>Hillsborough - $1000 (1 child); $1500 (2 children); $2000 (3+ children) \r\n</ul>',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,291,'2005-03-12 20:16:30',20071116195925,'2005-03-12 20:16:30');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9963429','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','$280,000 sounds like a huge goal. How is this possible to achieve?','Yes, $280,000 is a large sum of money considering there are less than 500 students and approximately 300 families. LPEF and the Loma and CT Home & School Clubs have joined together to create a year-long effort','Yes, $280,000 is a large sum of money considering there are approximately 500 students and 300 families. LPEF and the Loma and CT Home & School Clubs have joined together to create a year-long effort to support KEEP. Proceeds from the Gift Wrap, Halloween Carnival, LPEF Raffle and Auction and the upcoming Jogathan will also be contributed to help meet the KEEP campaign goal. However, the majority of funds are expected to be from parent and extended family contributions.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,198,'2005-03-12 20:15:23',20071024023652,'2005-03-12 20:15:23');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0002881','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','How did the program priorities get set? Can parents earmark funds to specific programs?','Superintendent Castaniada began soliciting suggestions in late 2005, and presented prelminary recommendations to the Superintendent\\\'s Coordinating Council, LPEF and the Loma Home and School Club in January. Additionally, Henry and Principal Diana Hallock presented the priority list to teachers and the School Board.','Superintendent Castaniada began soliciting suggestions in late 2005, and presented a preliminary priority slate to the Superintendent\\\'s Coordinating Council, LPEF and the Loma Home and School Club in January. A final priority slate was presented and approved by the LPEF Governing Board on February 6, 2006. Additionally, Henry and Principal Diana Hallock presented the priority list to teachers and the School Board.  No, donors cannot request that contributions go toward a specific program.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,393,'2005-03-12 20:14:02',20070915150918,'2005-03-12 20:14:02');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0081652','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','If the KEEP Campaign raises more than $280,000 what other programs would be funded?','We want to have this challenge! Feedback from parents following the success of the 2005 KEEP Campaign has helped shape the 2006 program priority list. While the official target is $280,000, the full KEEP slate actually totals $314,000. Parents will know how \\\"extra\\\" funds will be utilized by reviewing the priority list. ','We want to have this challenge! Feedback from parents following the success of the 2005 KEEP Campaign has helped shape the 2006 program priority list. While the official target is $280,000, the full KEEP slate actually totals $314,000. Parents will know how \\\"extra\\\" funds will be utilized by reviewing the priority list. Programs are listed in priority order, and program costs are estimates; actual costs will be determined by the district and approved by LPEF. To save teaching positions and rescind layoff notices, donations must be received by May 1, 2006.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,201,'2005-03-12 20:13:21',20070915150947,'2005-03-12 20:13:21');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0223077','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','As parents, how do we provide input to the program priorities?','Parents have many ways to be heard: volunteer with organizations like LPEF or the Home and School Clubs or the Site Councils, attend School Board Budget Study Sessions, or contact Principal Diana Hallock or Superintendent Henry Castaniada.','Parents have many ways to be heard: volunteer with organizations like LPEF or the Home and School Clubs or the Site Councils, attend School Board Budget Study Sessions, or contact Principal Diana Hallock or Superintendent Henry Castaniada.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,117,'2005-03-12 20:12:43',20070608013155,'2005-03-12 20:12:43');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0360404','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Do the teachers support this campaign?','Yes, teachers from Loma and CT English support the KEEP campaign.','Yes, teachers from Loma and CT English support the KEEP campaign.\r\n',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,172,'2005-03-12 20:11:00',20071116232719,'2005-03-12 20:11:00');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0504193','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What happens if we dont raise enough money?','Teacher layoff notices if not rescinded by 5/15 become final. Based on results of the KEEP campaign, the school board will act to rescind layoff notices and inform classified employees (for developmental PE, and library services) what their employment status for the next school year will be.','Teacher layoff notices if not rescinded by 5/15 become final. Based on results of the KEEP campaign, the school board will act to rescind layoff notices and inform classified employees (for developmental PE, and library services) what their employment status for the next school year will be.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,169,'2005-03-12 20:10:08',20071116111851,'2005-03-12 20:10:08');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0610193','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Why conduct the campaign now?','All hiring decisions for next school year must be finalized for teachers by May 15. A final budget for next year must be adopted by June 30; therefore the district must be assured of the money by May 1 so that they may rescind layoff notices. One other major Fundraising event, the Jogathon,','All hiring decisions for next school year must be finalized for teachers by May 15. A final budget for next year must be adopted by June 30; therefore the district must be assured of the money by May 1 so that they may rescind layoff notices. One other major Fundraising event, the Jogathon, will take place after May 1, so the KEEP committee will receive an estimate from the Loma H&SC for the expected contribution from Jogathon proceeds. ',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,184,'2005-03-12 20:09:10',20071116205430,'2005-03-12 20:09:10');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('07/04/22/8367073','Y',NULL,'67.180.134.253','19','KEEP Frequently Asked Questions','KEEP Frequently Asked Questions','Why do we need a special fundraising campaign?\r\n\r\nWe need to raise money, on an annual basis, to maintain excellent educational programs for our children. Unfortunately, maintaining smaller class sizes, a robust middle school curriculum and \r\nproviding means to future innovation is tied to annual fundraising since the revenues provided by the State are simply not enough to pay for broad educational programs. The district will be forced to make significant cuts in staffing and programs next school year if we do not reach our KEEP campaign goal. This budget situation has been developing over the last several years and is the result of declining enrollment and dramatic increases in mandated program costs, such as Special Education. Although the district has tapped reserves in past years to pay for smaller class sizes and programs, as of two years ago there are no more reserves available to augment the revenue from the state. Consequently, 90% of the districts unrestricted funds are spent on salaries and benefits. Without a successful KEEP campaign 2 teaching positions will be eliminated, and numerous programs must be eliminated or reduced (such as CT Elective classes, Developmental PE, Library Services, Student Counseling and MVP). \r\n\r\nHow much money is needed?\r\n\r\nSuperintendent Henry Castaniada has identified $245,000 to $305,000 as the campaign target. If successful, the following positions and programs will be funded (in the order listed): \r\n<li>K-8 Staffing to optimize class sizes ($65,000)\r\n<li>Developmental PE ($55,000)\r\n<li>K-8 Staffing to optimize class sizes ($65,000)  \r\n<li>MVP (Music, Visual and Performing Arts) ($15,000)  \r\n<li>Library Services ($5,000)\r\n<li>Student Counseling ($5,000)\r\n<li>K-8 Staffing (½ position) to optimize class sizes ($35,000)\r\n\r\n<li>Technology updates and upgrades ($10,000)\r\n<li>Math Computer Lab ($20,000) \r\n<li>Library computer upgrades ($10,000)\r\n<li>Science Activity Lab ($10,000) \r\n<li>Foreign Language Program ($10,000)\r\n\r\nWhat is the suggested donation per family?\r\n\r\nThe suggested family contributions to the KEEP campaign are the same as previous years: $600 for one child and $900 if you have more than one child in the district. However, families are asked to participate in other school fundraising efforts during the year for a total contribution of $1,200 for one child and $1,800 for more than one child (e.g., Gift Wrap, Halloween Carnival, Gala Auction and Jogathon).\r\n\r\nIs my KEEP contribution tax deductible?\r\n\r\nYes! LPEF is a non-profit 501(c)3 corporation and, therefore, all contributions are 100% tax deductible. \r\n\r\nWhat if our family isnt able to donate the suggested amount?\r\n\r\nEvery donation makes a difference. Please contribute an amount that is comfortable for your family. The recommended amounts are suggestions and not requirements. It is the donations of each family, our friends, and community members that collectively add up to the grand total raised each year.\r\n\r\nWhat do other local Education Foundations suggest as donations?\r\n\r\nHere\\\'s the suggested donations from comparable districts in the bay area: \r\n·Los Gatos- $600 (1 child); $900 (2 or more children) \r\n·Saratoga - $700 (1 child); $1400 (2 children); $2100 (3+ children) \r\n·Los Altos - $700 (1 child); $1400 (2 children); $2100 (3+ children) \r\n·Menlo Park/ Atherton - $500 (1 child); $1000 (2 children); $1500 (3+ children) \r\n·Hillsborough - $1000 (1 child); $1500 (2 children); $2000 (3+ children)\r\n·Mill Valley - $500 (1 child); $1000 (2 children); $1500 (3+ children)\r\n\r\nHow do program priorities get set?\r\n\r\nThe funding priorities have been identified by the Superintendent based on the needs of the entire district. The funding priorities are then submitted to the LPEF Governing Board, which must approve each item on the list (considered program awards). The program awards are then presented to the school district, and as with all donations, ultimately the school board decides to accept or reject the program awards. \r\n\r\nAs parents, how do we provide input to the program priorities?\r\n\r\nParents have many ways to be heard: volunteer with organizations like LPEF, the Home and School Clubs or the School Site Councils; attend School Board Budget Study Sessions; and/or meet with Superintendent Henry Castaniada to discuss your ideas. \r\n\r\nCan parents earmark their KEEP donation for a specific program(s?\r\n\r\nNo, donors cannot request that contributions go toward a specific program. \r\n\r\nHow is company matching handled?\r\n\r\nMany corporations offer matching donation programs. If your company matches personal contributions to charitable organizations, you may be able to double your contribution by simply requesting a matching donation from your company. You must initiate the matching contribution by requesting and completing a special form from your company. The forms are typically available in the human resource department or on company web sites.\r\n\r\nWhat happens if the KEEP Campaign exceeds its goal?\r\n\r\nWe would love to have this challenge! While the official target is $245,000, the full KEEP slate actually totals $305,000. Parents will know how \\\"extra\\\" funds will be utilized by looking to the second tier of the priority list. \r\n\r\nDo the teachers support this campaign?\r\n\r\nYes, teachers are vocal supporters of this parent-driven effort to raise funds for Loma and CT English. \r\n\r\nWhat happens if we dont raise enough money?\r\n\r\nIn the case of teaching positions, layoff notices not be rescinded by May 12, as in prior years. Other program cuts would be phased in as deemed appropriate by the Superintendent and Principal.\r\n\r\nWhy conduct the campaign now?\r\n\r\nBy State law, all hiring decisions for next school year must be finalized for teachers by May 12 and a final district budget for 2007-2008 must be adopted by June 30. Therefore, the Superintendent and Board of Trustees must know how much revenue (including KEEP donations) it will have available by May 1.\r\n\r\nIs fundraising the only answer? \r\n\r\nYes, if we want to continue to offer an enriched curriculum for our children and maintain small class sizes in grades 4-8. \r\n\r\nWill we need to raise this amount of money every year? \r\n\r\nYes. California schools are under funded, ranking near the bottom in the nation. The Loma Prieta School District per student rate is the fifth lowest in the state. The District cannot get this per-pupil funding rate changed. There have been lawsuits throughout California by other low-funded districts and the courts have held that as long as the per-pupil rates are within 10% of each other, it is legal to fund districts so differently. \r\nThe school district barely receives sufficient funds from the State to pay for teachers and a district office. Only those communities who value strong public schools and have the means are able to also offer programs in PE, sports, the arts, technology, library services and smaller class sizes. We are fortunate that our small Loma Prieta community is willing to make our schools a priority. \r\n\r\nHow can I get more involved in the campaign?\r\n\r\nAdditional volunteers are always needed. Please contact Charlotte Boisvert-Khandelwal, Campaign chairperson, at (home) 353-4530 or (email) charndante@hotmail.com.\r\n\r\nWhy are both the Home & School Clubs and LPEF raising money for the schools?\r\n\r\nThe Home & School Clubs raise money for school-specific expenses such as buying teaching supplies, playground equipment, as well as to fund special events. Home & School Clubs are not allowed to pay for salaries of aides and other staff. LPEF raises money to fund district-wide programs such music, P.E., art, library services, counseling, science and technology, as well as class size reduction.\r\n\r\nWhat are the accounting procedures for contributions to the KEEP Campaign? \r\n\r\nLPEF is a 501(c)3 corporation, with strict fiduciary responsibilities with regard to funds raised. All checks and credit card payments will be held in LPEF checking/savings accounts. \r\n\r\nHow often will LPEF produce financial reports on the KEEP Campaign? \r\n\r\nA report detailing the revenue received and the expenses incurred (e.g., postage, printing) during the Keep Campaign will be posted on the LPEF website as soon as practical after the end of the campaign. Reports detailing expenses and payments to the district will be available on a quarterly basis. Additionally KEEP campaign financial reporting will occur as part of LPEFs regular accounting reports.\r\n\r\nWhat will LPEF do to ensure KEEP Campaign funds are spent on the priority list? \r\n\r\nPayments to the district will be made after the district has incurred expenses and supplied LPEF with detailed documentation of those expenses. The district will supply Conditional Funding Approval Documents that are fiscal and program reports that document funds are being used based upon the priority list. If all funds raised are not spent in a particular year, they will be rolled forward to the next years KEEP Campaign.\r\n\r\nKEEP Campaign Parcel Tax Questions\r\n\r\nWhat about the Parcel Tax? \r\n\r\nThe District has had a $150 parcel tax for the past 15 years. Historically the parcel tax revenues were sufficient to pay for student programs in technology, arts, nurse, library services, developmental PE and maintenance and operations. However, over time program costs have increased while the parcel tax revenues have remained $150 since 1991.\r\n\r\nDo we really need a Parcel Tax and the KEEP Campaign? \r\n\r\nYes! Most of our neighboring districts also supplement their state funding with local parcel taxes and annual district-wide fundraising campaigns. Without additional income from parcel tax dollars and a successful KEEP campaign we will be required to reduce staff and/or eliminate our current student enrichment programs. Parcel taxes in other districts that also have educational funds are: \r\nLos Gatos	$290	\r\nLos Altos	over $600\r\nPalo Alto	over $600	\r\nLoma Prieta 	$150\r\n\r\nAre seniors exempt from the Parcel Tax? \r\n\r\nYes, senior citizens 65 and older may apply for an exemption at the District Office.\r\n',NULL,'Lydia Dobyns','lydia@gmail.com','',1,122,'2007-04-22 12:12:48',20071114210218,'2007-04-22 12:12:48');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0801701','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What will happen in the fall with fundraising requests?','The KEEP campaign, now in its second year, is an annual Cash Contribution campaign, and has replaced the LPEF and the Loma and CT Home & School Clubs Sponsorship and Pledge Drive Campaigns, formerly conducted during the \\\'back-to-school\\\' timeframe.','The KEEP campaign, now in its second year, is an annual Cash Contribution campaign, and has replaced the LPEF and the Loma and CT Home & School Clubs Sponsorship and Pledge Drive Campaigns, formerly conducted during the \\\'back-to-school\\\' timeframe.  In effect, this now allows parents to write one check, in the spring, instead of 3 sponsorship checks in the fall. Given the large KEEP Campaign goal, all school service organizations are working together to coordinate fundraising activities throughout the school year. The LPEF Gala will be back on October 7, 2006 and all proceeds from the Gala will be used for the 2007 KEEP Campaign.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,83,'2005-03-12 20:07:21',20070624135200,'2005-03-12 20:07:21');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/0970891','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Is fundraising the only answer?','Yes, if we want to continue to offer an enriched curriculum for our children.  State money barely covers teachers in the classroom!','Yes, if we want to continue to offer an enriched curriculum for our children.  State money barely covers teachers in the classroom!',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,73,'2005-03-12 20:06:10',20070422120845,'2005-03-12 20:06:10');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/1006297','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Will we need to raise this amount of money every year?',' Yes, A sad reality about funding for public schools in California is that the per-pupil-revenues school districts receive barely pay for a teacher in a classroom and the cost to run a district. Only those communities who value strong public schools and have the means are able to also offer programs in','Yes, A sad reality about funding for public schools in California is that the per-pupil-revenues school districts receive barely pay for a teacher in a classroom and the cost to run a district. Only those communities who value strong public schools and have the means are able to also offer programs in PE, sports, the arts, technology, library services and smaller class sizes. While California used to enjoy a position of excellence in public schools, the state is now notorious for having gone from First to Worst in per student funding in public education. We are fortunate that our small Loma Prieta community is willing to make strong, local schools a priority. First to Worst is a public television documentary that focuses on the decline of California public education. If you are interested in viewing this documentary, contact Henry Castaniada in the district office.',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,156,'2005-03-12 20:05:46',20071117065245,'2005-03-12 20:05:46');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/1087861','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What are the accounting procedures for contributions to the KEEP Campaign?','All checks and credit card payments will be held in LPEF Checking/Savings Accounts.  We are a 501(c)3 corporation, with strict fiduciary responsibilities with regard to funds raised.  As with other fundraising programs LPEF has conducted, these funds will be clearly designated as Keep Campaign Revenues.','All checks and credit card payments will be held in LPEF Checking/Savings Accounts.  We are a 501(c)3 corporation, with strict fiduciary responsibilities with regard to funds raised.  As with other fundraising programs LPEF has conducted, these funds will be clearly designated as Keep Campaign Revenues.  Expense s(such as credit card fees, postage and printing, payments to the district,  etc) will be documented and delineated in all financial reports. ',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,169,'2005-03-12 20:03:07',20071116111846,'2005-03-12 20:03:07');
