INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/9239622','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','What is the KEEP campaign?','KEEP stands for <U>K</U>eep <u>E</u>xcellent <u>E</u>ducation <u>P</u>rograms','KEEP stands for <i><U>K</U>eep <u>E</u>xcellent <u>E</u>ducation <u>P</u>rograms</i>, and is a Coordinated Fundraiser campaign supported by:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Loma Prieta Home & School Club\r\n<li>CT English Home & School Club\r\n<li>Loma Site Council\r\n<li>CT English Site Council\r\n<li>Loma Prieta Community Foundation\r\n<li>Loma and CT Teachers\r\n<li>District employees\r\n<li>Superintendent Henry Castaniada\r\n<li>Principal Diana Hallock\r\n<li>Chief Business Official Don Fox\r\n</ul>',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','keep@lpef.org','http://www.lpef.org',1,231,'2005-03-12 20:22:01',20071014220047,'2005-03-12 20:22:01');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/12/5580600','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','20','Loma Prieta School District\'s KEEP Campaign Ends May 1st','Remember when you were in school? We had art and music classes, home\r\neconomics and woodshop. Your parents\\\' friends and neighbors helped\r\nsupport this enriched education with their tax dollars and plenty of\r\nfunding from the state. That is not the case anymore. California\r\nschools are in crisis. California','Remember when you were in school? We had art and music classes, home\r\neconomics and woodshop. Your parents\\\' friends and neighbors helped\r\nsupport this enriched education with their tax dollars and plenty of\r\nfunding from the state. That is not the case anymore. California\r\nschools are in crisis. California is 49th out of the 50 states in\r\nspending per pupil. Over the past five years, the children in\r\nCalifornia public schools have had education services reduced by $9\r\nbillion.\r\n\r\nWhat does this have to do with Loma Prieta? A budget crisis has been developing over the last several years and is the result of dramatic increases in mandated program costs, such as Special Education, (over which the district has no control), and declining enrollment. Although the district has tapped reserves in past years to pay for smaller class sizes and programs, as of last year there are no more reserves available to augment the revenue from the state. Consequently 90% of the districts unrestricted expenditures are spent on salaries and benefits. \r\n\r\nWithout a successful KEEP campaign next year 2 teaching positions will be eliminated, and numerous programs must be eliminated or reduced (such as 50% of CT Elective classes, Developmental PE, Library Services, Student Counseling and MVP). \r\n\r\nMeasure K bond money is completely separate from the District\\\'s\r\noperating funds and cannot be used for any purpose other than the\r\nvoter-approved project list.\r\n\r\nSuperintendent Henry Castaniada has identified $280,000 to $314,000 as the campaign target. If successful, the following priority list of jobs and programs will be funded in this order: \r\n1.  2 Teaching positions saved. This will allow the district to maintain a variety of elective offerings at CTE, maintain smaller class sizes in Grades 4-8, provide instruction, at the middle school in Technology. $150,000 \r\n2.  Maintain Library Services at both schools, $22,000 \r\n3.  Developmental PE at Loma, $53,000\r\n4.  Student counseling at both schools, $12,000 \r\n5.  MVP (Music, Visual and Performing Arts) at Loma, $15,000 \r\n6.  Technology updates and upgrades for K-8 ($8,000) \r\n7.  New Loma Science Activity Lab Created ($20,000) \r\n8.  Foreign Language: 4th-5th grades ($10,000) \r\n9.  New Music Classes ($14,000) \r\n10. New K-8 Library System ($10,000) \r\n\r\n\r\nFamilies are being asked to contribute $600 if they have one child or\r\n$900 for two or more children. We know that there are families that\r\njust cannot afford this. That is where you come in, as friend,\r\nneighbor, community member, public education supporter or child\r\nadvocate. Please consider sponsoring a child or a family in this\r\ncampaign. The KEEP campaign replaces the September back-to-school\r\npledge and sponsorship drives conducted by LPEF and Home and school\r\nClubs. Parents supporting this fundraiser can take comfort that they\r\nwill not be asked to write sponsorship checks again in September.\r\n\r\nSupport for this key effort comes not only from parents and administration but teachers as well.\r\n   \r\nCTE teacher Sharon Dahnert says, \\\"The Loma and CT teachers support the KEEP campaign. We greatly appreciate the parent and community\r\ncommitment to excellence for our wonderful mountain students.\\\"\r\n\r\nPledge forms can be found at <a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org\\\">www.lpef.org</a>\r\nor by calling LPEF at 566-3007.\r\n\r\nWe need your support today. Thank you.\r\n',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','ldobyns@gmail.com','http://www.lpef.org',1,336,'2005-03-12 22:33:00',20071014051028,'2005-03-12 22:33:00');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('06/03/06/3722599','Y',NULL,'198.144.199.78','21','2006 Sponsorship Opportunities',' We invite current and potential sponsors to email <a href=\\\"mailto:charndante@hotmail.com\\\">Charlotte Boisvert-Khandelwal</a> or <a href=\\\"mailto:VaughanLJ@yahoo.com\\\">Lauri Vaughan</a> to sign-up for exciting sponsorhip opportunities throughout the year. For the first time, sponsors may consolidate','We invite current and potential sponsors to email <a href=\\\"mailto:charndante@hotmail.com\\\">Charlotte Boisvert-Khandelwal</a> or <a href=\\\"mailto:VaughanLJ@yahoo.com\\\">Lauri Vaughan</a> to sign-up for exciting sponsorhip opportunities throughout the year. For the first time, sponsors may consolidate participation in all major fundraising events, including the KEEP campaign, the Gala and the Jogathon with one contact person.\r\n<p>\r\nDownload the <a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/06_Sponsorship_03_02.pdf\\\">LPEF 2006 Sponsorship Opportunities</a> matrix now.',NULL,'Lydia Dobyns','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,218,'2006-03-06 00:42:02',20071116111907,'2006-03-06 00:42:02');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/13/4495777','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','20','Why We Need The KEEP Campaign','See for yourself the dramatic impact a successful KEEP Campaign can have for our children next year with your support.','<center><h3>KEEP Stands for <i><U>K</U>eep <u>E</u>xcellent <u>E</u>ducation <u>P</u>rograms</i></h3></center>\r\n\r\n<center><h3>A Groundbreaking Coordinated Fundraiser for Loma Prieta Schools</h3></center>\r\n\r\n<TABLE border=1>\r\n<tr><td width=\\\"49%\\\" ALIGN=center>\r\n<h3>NEXT YEAR<br>\r\nWITHOUT HELP FROM KEEP</h3>\r\n</td><td WIDTH=\\\"49%\\\" align=center>\r\n<h3>NEXT YEAR<br>\r\nWITH $280,000 TO $314,000 KEEP PROCEEDS</h3>\r\n</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td valign=top><h3 align=center>2006-2007 School Year</h3><ul>\r\n<li>2 teaching positions eliminated\r\n<li>Combination classes in K-5 likely\r\n<li>Library Services Reduced\r\n<li>Developmental PE eliminated\r\n<li>CTE Elective classes reduced by 50%<br>\r\n<li>Music,Visual & Performing Arts eliminated\r\n<li>Loma/CTE Counseling eliminated\r\n<li>No Loma Science Activity Lab\r\n<li>No Foreign Language 4-5 grades\r\n<li>No New Music Classes\r\n<li>No Library System Upgrade\r\n</ul>\r\n</td><td valign=top><h3 align=center>2006-2007 School Year</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2 teaching positions saved ($150,000)\r\n<br>Smaller class sizes 4-8 grades\r\n<br>CTE Elective program saved\r\n<li>Library Aides saved ($22,000)\r\n<li>Developmental PE saved ($53,000)\r\n<li>Loma/CTE Student Counseling saved ($12,000)\r\n<li>Music, Visual & Performing Arts saved ($15,000)\r\n<li>Technology updates and upgrades for K-8 ($8,000)\r\n<li>New Loma Science Activity Lab Created ($20,000)\r\n<li>Foreign Language for 4-5 grades ($10,000)\r\n<li>New Music Classes ($14,000)\r\n<li>New K-8 Library System ($10,000)\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr><td colspan=2 align=\\\"left\\\">\r\nTo save teachers and programs, we must have your donation by May 1.<p>\r\nPrograms are listed in priority order, program costs are estimates; actual costs will be determined by the district and approved by LPEF. The complete KEEP slate as listed is $314,000. Donation forms are downloadable from <b><a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/portal.php?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lpef.org%2Flocal%2F06_KEEP-Pledge-Form-and-Summary.pdf&what=T_Links&rid=06/03/04/1836454\\\">this link</a></b>, and available at the CTE or Loma offices.\r\n</td></tr></table>',NULL,'KEEP Campaign Committee','ldobyns@gmail.com','http://www.lpef.org',1,437,'2006-03-06 00:42:31',20071114182252,'2005-03-21 17:41:35');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/13/9339441','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','22','It\'s Time for  Auction Donations: Can You Help?','LPEF volunteers are busy seeking auction donations for the 2005 Gala to be held on October 7, 2006. You can help!','Looking for more ways to help the kids? Turn your connections into cash. Local businesses get inundated with requests for donations to school auctions. (We know, were asking, too!) Many small business owners will donate if they know they are helping a loyal patron. When we approach merchants, we at LPEF often get asked if a member of our community visits that business or is a member of a particular golf club. If we can say yes and give them a name, they would readily give us a generous donation. If you frequent a restaurant, salon, store, or hotel, or are a member of a local golf club, you can help us with auction donations. You can ask for a donation directly or give us the information and someone from LPEF will ask on your behalf. \r\n\r\nIf you are a small business owner or know someone who is, remember all donations are tax deductible. If a business you know is trying to develop a client base, they can sponsor a highly visible live auction package and receive great visibility at the Gala. If you have suggestions, if youre willing to help us get auction donations or have questions, please contact Julie Bourque at jbourque@loma.k12.ca.us or Gretchen Goosey, Gretchen@Goosey.com\r\n',NULL,'Gretchen Goosey','Gretchen@Goosey.com','',1,387,'2005-03-13 21:48:59',20071116153512,'2005-03-13 21:48:59');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/03/21/7046890','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','19','Parcel Tax Questions and Answers','<center><b>KEEP Campaign Parcel Tax Questions</b></center>\r\n\r\n<center><b>What About the Parcel Tax Dollars? </b></center>\r\n\r\nThe District has had the same $150 parcel tax for the past 15 years. Historically the parcel tax revenues were sufficient to pay for student programs in technology, arts, nurse, library services, developmental PE and maintenance',' <center><b>KEEP Campaign Parcel Tax Questions</b></center>\r\n\r\n<center><b>What About the Parcel Tax? </b></center>\r\n\r\nThe District has had the same $150 parcel tax for the past 15 years. Historically the parcel tax revenues were sufficient to pay for student programs in technology, arts, nurse, library services, developmental PE and maintenance and operations. However, over time program costs have increased while the parcel tax revenues have remained $150 since 1991. In addition, significant income has been lost due to declining enrollment in the past five years.\r\n\r\n\r\n<center><b>Cant We Get More Money From The State?</b></center>\r\n\r\nIt\\\'s no secret that California schools are under funded, ranking near the bottom in the nation. The Loma Prieta per student rate is the fifth lowest in the state. The District cannot get this per-pupil funding rate changed. There have been lawsuits throughout California by other low-funded districts and the courts have held that as long as the per-pupil rates are within 10% of each other, it is legal to fund districts so differently.\r\n\r\n<center><b>Where Does The Money From The Parcel Tax Go? </b></center>\r\n\r\nIn the current year parcel tax income is being used to <u><i>partially pay</i></u> for:\r\n<table border=0><tr><td><ul>\r\n<li>Smaller Class Size ($131,000)\r\n<li>Technology Programs and Technology Support ($88,000)\r\n<li>Equip and Maintain the schools, facilities and grounds ($52,000)\r\n<li>Health Services ($12,000) \r\n</ul></td></tr></table>\r\n\r\n\r\n<center><b>Do We Really Need A Parcel Tax And The KEEP Campaign?</b></center>\r\n\r\nYES! Most of our neighboring districts also supplement their state funding with local parcel taxes and annual district-wide fundraising campaigns. Without additional income from parcel tax dollars and a successful KEEP campaign we will be required to reduce and/or eliminate our current student enrichment programs. \r\n\r\n<center><b>Are Seniors Exempt From The Parcel Tax?</b></center>\r\n\r\nYes, Senior citizens 65 and older may apply for an exemption at the School District Office. \r\n',NULL,'The Keep Campaign Committee','ldobyns@gmail.com','',1,187,'2005-03-11 20:50:46',20071112145438,'2005-03-11 20:50:46');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/09/28/0420909','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','3','LPEF Governing Board and Committee Openings','Interested in joining LPEF, either as a governing board member or a committee member? New terms start in January 2006. ','<b>LPEF Mission:</b> LPEF is a non-profit corporation founded in 2001 committed to raise money to enhance the educational experience for all students within the Loma Prieta School District. Since its inception, LPEF has raised more than $600,000 to directly benefit our local K-8 public schools. The Education Fund meets regularly with the Superintendent to develop funding priorities. Monies are then awarded as specific program grants to the District and include accountability and measurement criteria. LPEF is modeled after successful foundations long established throughout California that work to address critical funding shortages. LPEF complements the Loma and CT English Home and School Clubs and is committed to active collaboration with all parent groups to best meet the districts needs.\r\n\r\n<b>Organizational Structure:</b> LPEF is an all-volunteer organization that is administered by a governing board of up to 15 people. From within the Governing Board an Executive Steering Committee is appointed annually to oversee all operations. Standing committees of LPEF include the KEEP Campaign, the Gala Committee and Program Award and Accountability Committee. Volunteers are welcome as Governing Board members or non-voting committee members. \r\n\r\nTypically LPEF board members serve 2-year terms, which begin in January. LPEF seeks to increase K-5 and 6-8 parent representatives. While all LPEF board members are expected to volunteer, not all positions require equal time commitments; average monthly commitments range from 5 to 15 hours per month.\r\n\r\n<b>Responsibilities of Governing Board Members:</b>\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>Provide Philanthropic leadership\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Make a personal annual gift of any amount\r\n<li>Support fundraising objectives through attendance at special events and solicitation of in-kind gifts and sponsorships\r\n<li>Assist in resource development through identification of potential donors or funding sources\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Provide Strategic Guidance and Planning\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Review and monitor policies and by-laws to ensure LPEF continues to operate within adopted by-laws and the scope of mission\r\n<li>Participate in long and short-range planning to achieve goals\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Financial and Legal Stewardship\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Authorize and approve an annual budget and accounting review\r\n<li>Assist with the development of annual financial goals\r\n<li>Ensure LPEF meets legal requirements\r\n<li>Ensure funds raised are allocated according to donor intent and in the best interest of all students in the LPJUSD\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Program Award Approval\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Review and approve program awards requested by the Superintendent and submitted for approval by the LPEF Executive Steering Committee\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Outreach\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Understand, articulate and advocate LPEFs mission in the community\r\n<li>Cultivate and enlist key community leader support for LPEF\r\n<li>Identify and recruit volunteers: Board and committee members\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nWe invite anyone interested in volunteering with LPEF to attend the next board meeting on Nov 7th at 7pm. Call Pat McGrath (353-2144), Julie Gouldsberry (353-8223) or Lydia Dobyns (353-2433) for more information.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b><u><a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/local/05_LPEF_Recruitment.pdf\\\">Download the Flyer</a></u></b><p>',NULL,'Lydia Dobyns','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,292,'2005-09-28 05:27:00',20071116112541,'2005-09-28 05:27:00');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/11/08/9558641','Y',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','3','2006 LPEF Governing Board Elected','Elections were held on November 8, 2005 for the 2006 LPEF Governing Board.','Elections were held on November 8, 2005 for the 2006 LPEF Governing Board. Re-elected to new two year terms were Lydia Dobyns, Barry Dobyns, Pat McGrath, and Peggy Johnson. Elected for the first time, also for two year terms, were: Julie Bourque, Melanie Earhart, Paula Lacey and Charlotte Khandelwal. Continuing board members include Julie Gouldsberry, Gretchen Goosey, Jodi Ridgway and Lauri Vaughan. Also elected as Ex Officio board members were Superintendent Henry Castaniada and Principal Diana Hallock.',NULL,'Lydia Dobyns','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,261,'2005-11-08 14:39:18',20071116134004,'2005-11-08 14:39:18');
INSERT INTO `T_Stories` VALUES ('05/11/08/0134836','N',NULL,'nat.dobyns.com','20','2006 KEEP Campaign Goals',' To maintain the same educational programs next year, we will need to raise an estimated $250,000. However, our goal is $280,000 to allow the district to implement new programs.\r\n\r\nHow will we do this? By working together! A coordinated year-long fundraising effort is planned by LPEF and the Home & School','To maintain the same educational programs next year,that were saved due to the success of the 2005 KEEP Campaign, we will need to raise an estimated $250,000 by May 1, 2006. However, our goal is $280,000 to allow the district to implement new programs.\r\n\r\nHow will we do this? By working together! A coordinated year-long fundraising effort is planned by LPEF and the Home & School Clubs, culminating in the actual KEEP cash campaign that ends May 1, 2006. The suggested family contributions are: $600 for one child and $900 for more than one child. However, assuming the same percentage of families participate this year, every family needs to approach this year with a new mission: combine your KEEP cash contribution with supporting other fundraising activities to reach a total contribution per family of $1,200 for one child and $1,800 for more than one child.\r\n\r\nYour donation is 100% tax deductible.\r\nInformation and pledge forms\r\nare available in each school office and at www.lpef.org. The Loma Public Education Fund is a 501(c) 3 non-profit corporation.\r\n\r\nThe 2005 KEEP Promise:\r\n·	Save 2 teaching positions\r\n·	Maintain K-8 smaller class sizes\r\n·	Restore 80% of CTE Electives \r\n·	Restore Reading Recovery to 80%\r\n·	Upgrade CTE Computer Lab\r\n·	Save Developmental PE\r\n·	Keep Student Counseling\r\n·	Keep Music & Arts at Loma\r\n·	Keep Library Services K-8\r\n·	Keep Yard Duty at 2004 Levels\r\n\r\nThe KEEP Reality in 2005-2006:\r\n·	Saved 2 teaching positions\r\n·	No Combination classes, avg class K-3: 20:1 students and 4-8: 26.4:1\r\n·	Restored 80% CT Electives\r\no	Spanish for 6, 7 & 8\r\no	Art\r\no	Speech & Debate\r\no	Technology\r\no	Study Skills\r\n·	Reading Remediation for 1st graders who qualify\r\n·	Brand new CTE Computer Lab, Implemented Technology Elective and Teacher Trainer\r\n·	Saved Loma Developmental PE\r\n·	Added Coordinator for CT Sports and Student Activities\r\n·	Kept Student Counseling\r\n·	Kept Music & Art at Loma\r\n·	Kept Library Services, K-8\r\n·	Kept Yard Duty at 2004 levels\r\n\r\n\r\nThe 2006 KEEP Steering Committee consists of the following volunteers:\r\nPat McGrath & Diane Matlock, Co-Chairs, Henry Castaniada, Joann Colombo, Lydia Dobyns, Melanie Earhart, Diana Hallock, Charlotte Khandelwal, Paula Lacey and Lauri Vaughan.',NULL,'Lydia Dobyns','lydia@dobyns.com','',1,209,'2005-11-08 14:48:54',20071113180422,'2005-11-08 14:48:54');
