INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (22,'barry','About the Loma Public Education Fund','2001-05-10 23:27:41','<h1>A short FAQ about LPEF</h1><br>','      <B>Mission:</B> <BR>\r\n      The Loma Public Education Fund (LPEF) is a non-profit corporation comprised of volunteers\r\n      committed to raise money to enhance the educational experience for students\r\n      in the Loma Prieta Joint Union School District. \r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>Why do we need an Education Fund?</B> <BR>\r\n      Founded in early 2001, a group of parents banded together to raise significant\r\n      money on an annual basis to preserve and enhance the District\'s ability to\r\n      offer outstanding educational programs as a vital part of the student\r\n      experience. \r\n      <P>\r\n      By raising funds for educational programs, the District can reallocate funds\r\n      to staff compensation, thus retaining current teachers and making our District\r\n      attractive for new teachers. \r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>Our goal is simple: raise money!</B> <BR>\r\n      The Fund serves solely to raise money. Fund members meet regularly with the\r\n      superintendent, principals, teachers and parents to develop funding priorities.\r\n      Monies are awarded as specific grants to the District, which include\r\n      accountability requirements and measurement criteria. \r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>Donations are 100% tax deductible.</B> <BR>\r\n      The Fund operates as a a 501(c)3, non-profit corporation and all donations to the Education Fund are tax\r\n      deductible. \r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>Funding Philosophy:</B> <BR>\r\n      The LPEF believes that the best educational experience is one that blends\r\n      academic achievement, the arts and sports. It is our goal to work with the\r\n      District, the Home and School Clubs, and School Site Councils to develop\r\n      coordinated funding strategies that best benefit our students. \r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>The LPEF Executive Steering Committee adopts funding priorities and conducts\r\n      annual assessments of all program grants. </B>\r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>Types of programs to fund:</B> <BR>\r\n      Following are kinds of programs and services the Fund may support: \r\n      <OL>\r\n    <LI>\r\n          reading intervention \r\n        <LI>\r\n          math and science intervention \r\n       <LI>\r\n          music and art instructors \r\n   <LI>\r\n          counseling interns \r\n  <LI>\r\n          librarians \r\n  <LI>\r\n          curriculum alignment for K-8 \r\n        <LI>\r\n          physical education / sports specialists \r\n     <LI>\r\n          computer and software \r\n       <LI>\r\n          technology personnel \r\n      </OL>\r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>Fund Raising Objectives:</B> <BR>\r\n      LPEF intends to contribute <B>$100,000</B> or more to the District during\r\n      the 2001-2002 school year. \r\n      <P>\r\n      <B>We need your help!</B>\r\n      <UL>\r\n   <LI>\r\n          Send us a cash contribution, suggested donations start at $250.  <BR>\r\n          Print out the <A HREF=\"LPEF-Pledge-Form-Aug-24.htm\">Pledge Form </A>\r\n      <LI>\r\n          Become a sponsor for the October 6th Gala\r\n <LI>\r\n          Donate new goods and/or services for the Gala\'s silent and live auction\r\n  <LI>\r\n          Volunteer to be part of this exciting organization. \r\n      </UL>',0,373,2,'barry','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','1');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (27,'lydia','CT Students Benefit From Reading Skills Grant','2002-08-03 18:49:46','Veteran CT English teachers Shelby Matlock, Kris Denues, and Melinda Chapin had an ongoing question during their years as language arts instructors.  &#8220;How do you address the individual needs of students in reading, when students of all reading levels are typically mixed in classes? How do you identify their needs and ensure that no student will fall through the cracks?&#8221;   \n','With the support of the administration and the school board, as well as a grant from LPEF for training, books, and other materials, the CT English Reading Program was instituted in Fall, 2002 to address these questions.  \n\nMs. Denues, Ms. Matlock, and Ms. Chapin, along with many other CT teachers, attended seminars and workshops geared towards enhancing reading skills, and then developed a program specifically addressing the needs of students at CTE  This is an exciting program, which Ms. Denues noted marked a &#8220;complete change&#8221; in the way reading has been taught at CTE  All CTE classroom teachers, as well as Principal Lorrie Wernick and Resource Teacher Carolyn Schmidt, teach two, 1-hour Reading Skills classes each week.  Ms. Denues, Matlock, and Chapin trained the CTE staff and with Principal Wernick continue to develop and review lesson plans with teachers.  The emphasis is on reading across the curriculum, which is geared toward improved reading in all classes.\n\nMs. Chapin has a goal for &#8220;every single student to be reading and comprehending well.  No student should drop through the cracks and at the same time, we want to challenge every reader.&#8221; To achieve this goal, CTE teachers use specific techniques, such as Socratic questioning.  There is no right answer to a Socratic question, but a student has to support his or her response with evidence from the text.  The students also appear more comfortable and willing to participate in the skill-based groups (see insert) than in the regular classroom setting.\n\nAs Ms. Denues noted, the Reading Program &#8220;may be one of the last chances for the students to really get formal reading instruction.&#8221;  One way to gauge its success is &#8220;if students can walk off this campus in June not feeling threatened by a piece of nonfiction writing, and if they feel comfortable picking up a book for fun.&#8221;  The effort and enthusiasm put into this program by Ms. Denues, Chapin, and Matlock, as well as the staff at CTE, cannot easily be put into words.  LPEF has been pleased to support this program which helps our middle school children be better readers, as well as more successful and prepared for the years ahead.\n\nThe Reading Program at CTE\n·	Students in each grade are placed in one of four skill-based groups based on SAT-9 Total Reading score\n·	Periodic assessment using Reading Concepts and STAR Reading Tests are performed for well-rounded assessments \n·	Skill-based groups are fluid- a student can move to different group as reading skills improve\n·	Program effectiveness will be evaluated at the end of the year\n·	Skill-based groups work on target areas (e.g., reading accuracy, comprehension, critical thinking) depending on need\n     ',0,310,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (23,'lydia','LPEF Grant helps Loma Elementary Adopt Reading Recovery Program in 2001','2002-08-03 17:59:14','When it came to choosing a reading intervention program at Loma, Principal/Superintendent Mary Ellen Lewis and the teachers at Loma knew what they wanted.  Second grade teachers Helga Dinning and Laurie Brandt approached Ms. Lewis about implementing Reading Recovery (RR) for the 2001-2002 school year. According to Ms. Brandt, &#8220;Reading Recovery (RR) is known among teachers as the most successful reading intervention program in English-speaking countries.&#8221;  \n\n','Ms. Dinning described RR as a &#8220;teacher-based, not materials-based, program&#8221;, which requires an intense training year as RR providers.  They attended a 5-day training in August and continue to train one night a week for 4 hours in Santa Cruz.  Three times a year, they are observed and evaluated by their peers and their RR teacher leader, Bonnie Thurston.  She evaluates their administration of a RR session through a one-way mirror (called &#8220;Behind the Glass&#8221;).  Ms.Thurston also reviews the work and progress of LP students receiving RR intervention, and provides support and strategies with Ms. Dinning and Brandt to augment the training experience and provide the best services for the children.  Laurie Brandt commented that &#8220;using Reading Recovery techniques has lifted my own teaching,&#8221; and she finds herself using RR strategies with her 2nd graders.\n\nMs. Brandt reported that RR looks at each child individually by asking the question, &#8220;What specifically does this child need to learn today, tomorrow, this minute?&#8221;   In a typical RR session, a child will choose books he or she is familiar with to read in session, participate in a daily writing task, and work on breaking down the sounds in words.  The child also has nightly reading and writing homework to reinforce skills and strategies taught that day. Parents are invited to observe a lesson with their child.  \n\nMs. Dinning and Brandt communicate frequently with the kindergarten and first grade teachers to conference and assess the RR student&#8217;s reading and writing progress in the classroom.  RR targets the needs of the highest at-risk readers in first grade.  Children who do not make significant progress in RR can be referred for additional assessments early on, which will help identify children with learning disabilities before a cycle of failure begins.\n\nMs. Dinning stressed the importance of &#8220;building on what strategies a child already has; building on what they already know,&#8221; while Ms. Brandt noted that having children be independent readers in the classroom is a key goal.  They are passionate about this program and will assess these children for five years after program completion to evaluate the effectiveness of this intervention.  More information about RR can be found on their website (www.readingrecovery.org).    \n\nReading Recovery Facts\n·	Developed by Dr. Marie M. Clay in New Zealand\n·	An intervention program, not remediation (works with students before gaps in learning develop)\n·	Over 1 million children will be served by RR this year\n·	81% of students who completed RR read within the average range of their class by the end of first grade\n·	Data-collection from every RR site in the U.S. is sent to The National Center for Reading Recovery at Ohio State University to support research and evaluation of RR \n\nReading Recovery at Loma Prieta\n·	18 1st graders initially assessed\n·	16 children will have participated by the end of the year\n·	Each student receives individual intervention 30 minutes/session, 5 days/week for 16 to 20 weeks\n·	Of the 8 recent graduates, all were initially reading significantly below grade level- at program completion, all were reading at or beyond 1st grade standards\n\n\n\n  \n ',0,279,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
