INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (25,'lydia','LPEF Incorporated as Loma Public Education Fund','2002-08-03 18:30:00','When LPEF was formed in February 2001, we approached the Loma Prieta Community Foundation (LPCF) and asked for permission to operate under its legal structure. ','When LPEF was formed in February 2001, we approached the Loma Prieta Community Foundation (LPCF) and asked for permission to operate under its legal structure. The agreement with LPCF was for one year, so that we could focus on raising money for the 01-02 school year, through the Gala and Pledge Drive. \n\nWe are grateful to LPCF for their initial sponsorship. Contacting other educational foundations helped us shape the organizational structure for LPEF. Ultimately, for the cleanest management of funds, the LPEF Executive Steering Committee felt that we should be our own entity and voted in December 2001 to incorporate as a new, separate non-profit corporation. \n\nArticles of incorporation and applications for non-profit designation were completed in early 2002. As of July 1, 2002 LPEF received 501 (c) 3, non-profit status.   ',0,303,3,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (26,'lydia','Loma Public Education Fund Philosophy and Mission','2002-08-03 18:34:13','LPEF has structured itself to focus on fund-raising and awarding specific grants for programs administered by teachers and district staff.\n','Our District is small and enrollment is declining. If you&#8217;re following the news, you know that the State of California is in its worst financial predicament in years. School funding will be decreasing. If we want to retain excellent teachers, maintain current programs and foster innovation, we must bring new revenues into our schools. This is the primary focus for LPEF. \n\nLPEF has structured itself to focus on fund-raising and awarding specific grants for programs administered by teachers and district staff (like Reading Recovery). We do not seek grants from external organizations for LPEF per se, because we do not want to operate programs. We feel that it is the responsibility of the school board, administrators and teachers to determine educational policy, and to select and implement educational programs. We are pleased with the working relationships we&#8217;ve developed with District Staff. Raising money, is a HUGE job. Helping the District develop measurement criteria for each grant is another HUGE job. Recruiting and managing an all-volunteer organization is a HUGE job, well, you get the idea. We&#8217;re at our limit! \n\nLPEF works with the District to locate outside funding from local corporations and foundations to help share the costs of maintaining programs. Recently LPEF volunteers helped prepare a grant that the District submitted to Applied Materials for $69,500 to continue Reading Recovery. LPEF plans to help the District identify and submit grant proposals to help fund other programs initially paid for by LPEF grants.\n\nLPEF is a funding incubator for innovation. We want to help establish programs and then work with the District to find ways to become financially responsible for the ongoing program costs. We do not anticipate providing permanent funding for any program. By limiting ongoing funding for programs, we will be able to assist the District in piloting innovative programs year after year.  \n\n\n ',0,313,3,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (28,'lydia','Math Club and Counseling Services Aid CT students','2002-08-03 18:58:22','LPEF Funding Pays for After-School Math and Counseling Services at CT English','The After School Math Club is held two to four times a week with Cece Anderson at the helm.  Substitute teacher Nick Hoffman also works with students on afternoons when he is available.  One 8th grade participant commented, &#8220;Ms. Anderson makes it easier for tests because she has a study session before tests&#8221;, while another 8th grader offered, &#8220;It helps you get your homework done-with help!&#8221;  The LPEF also funds one day per week of counseling services for CTE students.',0,481,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (29,'lydia','Pilot Math Intervention Program Offered at Loma','2002-08-03 19:01:35','New math intervention program serves second through fifth graders.','Linda Smith taught 5th graders for four years, as well as two years at the middle school level, in the mid-70&#8217;s, but the kindergarten classroom is where she has worked since then.  This year, however, when a half-time position arose to get the LPEF-funded Math Intervention (MI) program off and running, it proved to be a good match for Ms. Smith and Loma Prieta. She noted, &#8220;I am absolutely loving it&#8230;working with older kids is very fun.&#8221;  Beginning this program, which serves second through fifth graders, was not without challenges. Ms. Smith is using a published intervention program called &#8220;Math Coach,&#8221; and it took time to get all the materials that were ordered, as well as become familiar with them. \n\nIn January, 38 students were initially referred to Ms. Smith based on SAT-9 math scores and teacher recommendation. Further assessments were completed with these students and 32 started in MI.  Ms. Smith works with groups of 3 to 6 children for half hour sessions, with most groups meeting four times a week.  There are two groups coming twice a week. Ms. Smith stressed that this is an intervention program based on California state standards. She is &#8220;not trying to duplicate what they&#8217;re working on in class,&#8221; but is working &#8220;to build a foundation and understand math rather than just help them with their homework.&#8221; Students are assessed periodically in the program, and Ms. Smith updates their classroom teachers on a regular basis. The overall effectiveness of Math Intervention will be evaluated at the end of the year.\n\nMs. Smith is pleased with feedback from teachers that students in MI are making progress in the classroom and they are &#8220;more careful in their thinking about math.&#8221;  LPEF is excited to support this program, which Ms. Smith views as an opportunity to &#8220;start working with children at a young age, help them so they don&#8217;t have these gaps and will be prepared for the grade ahead.&#8221;\n ',0,9959,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (31,'lydia','2002 Gala Sold Out!','2002-09-17 01:12:43','Tickets are sold out to One Enchanted Evening, the second annual gala fundraiser for LPEF to be held on October 5, 2002.','LPEF has established a waiting list for people who would like to purchase tickets. Call 408/566-3007. If you have tickets and find you are unable to attend, you may also call LPEF. The tickets are non-refundable, however, we are happy to help arrange private transactions between people who have tickets and those who would like to purchase tickets.\n\nAuction donations include fantastic school treasures from teachers and their classes. Also featured in the auction are fabulous vacations, beautiful jewelry, terrific wines and a large assortment of family outings and sports events. Tickets will be mailed the week of Sept 16, 2002. ',0,16770,4,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (32,'lydia','2002 Gala and Pledge Drive Successful','2003-01-21 23:32:58','One Enchanted Evening II held October 5th at the beautiful Maison du Luc was a resounding success, generating $40,000 for program grants for the Loma Prieta district schools.','This amount coupled with $43,000 raised so far in the community pledge drive brings the net fundraising total to $83,000 for the 2002-2003 school year. LPEF President Lydia Dobyns, estimated that the successes of the gala and the pledge drive were made possible by about 1,350 individual acts of kindness from 200 volunteers, 300 auction donors, 400 auction items, 350 ticket buyers and 100 pledge contributors.  This could not have happened without the dedication, enthusiasm, and energy that pulled everyone together for the benefit of the children in this community.   \n\nAnd what a fun party the gala was! The weather was perfect, the music great, and the food delicious.  The live auction featured six lots, with happy people winning front-row Sharks tickets, 49er tickets, a Los Gatos spa extravaganza for two, a winter vacation package to Lake Tahoe, and some exceptional wine.  There was something for everyone in the silent auction, whether you wanted to be pampered or needed something practical for your home or property.  Thanks to generous parents and community members, the net proceeds from the Gala grew by a whopping 43% over last year\'s results. \"The outpouring of support was phenomenal,\" said Lydia Dobyns, \"everywhere we turned to ask for something, the answer was usually \'yes\'.\"  \n\nLPEF has been working closely with the District to identify funding priorities, with approval given for the following program grants for the current school year: \n--Reading Recovery and Reading Intervention at Loma \n--School-wide Reading and Math Improvement Programs at C.T.E \n--7th period programs at C.T.E (featuring science, math and writing)\n--Sets of classroom textbooks at C.T.E. \n--Computers for IHS to support their educational programs.\n--Reading remediation for IHS students\n--Counseling services for both Loma and CT students\n--Technology Coordinator for Loma to help students and staff.  \n\n$17,000 More Is Needed to Make the$100,000 Goal for 2002-03.\n\nLPEF is close to reaching its $100,000 annual goal. We need to raise another $17,000 to reach our $100,000 goal. We\'re appealing to parents and community members who haven\'t yet contributed to please consider a donation, of any amount. Pledge forms are available from the LPEF website (www.lpef.org).  LPEF is also actively recruiting new members for the 2003 Executive Steering Committee.  If you are interested, please call 408/566-3007. Monthly meetings are held on the first Monday, from 7PM to 9PM.\n  ',0,229,4,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (33,'lydia','2003 Governing Board Elected and Executive Steering Committee Appointed','2003-01-21 23:43:18','The LPEF Governing Board for 2003 was elected at the annual meeting, held on January 13, 2003.','Re-elected Governing Board members are Julie Gouldsberry, Celia Maddox, Angela Patterson and Peggy Johnson. Continuing their multi-year terms on the Governing Board  are Adriana Chiocchi, Lydia Dobyns, Pat McGrath and Linda Sullivan. Newly elected Governing Board members are Suzy Kilby, Leslie O\'Malley and Sherrie Starkie. Executive Steering Committee (ESC) members were appointed by the Govering Board. ESC members for 2003 are: Lydia Dobyns, Pat McGrath, Linda Sullivan, Julie Gouldsberry, Celia Maddox, Angela Patterson, Suzy Kilby, Leslie O\'Malley and Sherrie Starkie. ',0,1209,3,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (40,'lydia','Reading Recovery 2004 Program Award','2004-09-06 18:35:01','LPEF is pleased to provide partial funding for the highly successful Reading Recovery program, now in its fourth year in the district.','The Reading Recovery program at Loma Prieta is administered by teachers Laurie Brandt and Helga Dinning. \n<A HREF=\"http://www.lpef.org/local/2004-05 Reading Recovery.pdf\">Reading Recovery Program Award</a>',0,58,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (35,'lydia','LPEF Program Grants Needed More than Ever','2003-06-21 15:03:08','The news is grim for everyone who values excellence in public school education. Schools throughout the state are facing huge budget cuts. Our District was hit with unprecedented midyear cuts and deferrals totaling more than $81,000, and faces $500,000 in new cuts for the 2003-2004 school year. Quite simply our local schools need financial help more than ever.','<p>\r\nAfter discussions with Superintendent/Principal Mary Ellen Johnson and CT English Principal Dr. Lorrie Wernick, LPEF has adopted the following funding priorities to help the District cope with shrinking state revenues next year:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Help maintain small class sizes throughout the elementary and middle schools.\r\n<p>\r\n<li>Preserve current academic enrichment and intervention programs.\r\n<p>\r\n<li>Continue to incubate new programs to address holes in strategic areas. Our initial areas of concentration were reading, math and writing. With successful fund raising, we hope to add a new program grant addressing technology gaps.\r\n<p>\r\n</ol>\r\nLPEF has guaranteed the District a minimum award pool for the 2003-2004 school year of $80,000, however, we need and want to do more. Our goal is to award $120,000 in program grants next year. We can only accomplish this with your help. Please contribute today. <a href=\\\"http://www.lpef.org/article.php?sid=17\\\">Print a pledge form.</a> ',0,201,2,'lydia','','2004-10-10 23:59:59','1');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (39,'lydia','2004 Program Award Grants Largest Ever for LPEF','2004-09-03 10:53:15','At the District\'s request, LPEF has committed over $100,000 in new grants for the 2004-05 school year.','By awarding early, LPEF helped the District retain all CT English teachers and save elective offerings at the middle school. Additionally, LPEF has committed to partial financial support for the Reading Recovery program, student counseling and technology upgrades.\n\nWe need to do more! Principal Diana Hallock, Superintendent Henry Castaniada and teachers have asked LPEF to fix a critical technology problem (the computer lab at Loma Prieta Elementary has incompatible computers, making it impossible for a whole class to use the same software); pay for the development of a Technology Curriculum for students and teaching staff; and provide funding for after-school enrichment at CT and Loma (such as continuing the Math Club with Ms. Anderson). We can do more with your help.\n\nOur goal is to raise $120,000 from the annual pledge drive and the October 2nd, 2004 Gala and Auction. With your help we will meet this goal.\n\nLPEF is asking every family in our district to help do whatever it takes to save and enhance our excellent local schools.  \n\n<A HREF=\"http://www.lpef.org/local/program awards letter 04-05.pdf\">Program Awards Letter</a>',0,97,2,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (37,'lydia','Get the 2004 Gala Ticket Form','2004-07-18 16:16:37','Get the 2004 Gala Ticket Form','Click here to download the <a href=http://www.lpef.org/local/2004%20Gala%20Ticket%20Order-2.pdf>2004 Gala Ticket form</a> and print a copy on your computer!',0,49715,2,'Barry','','2004-10-11 23:59:59','1');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (41,'lydia','Student Counseling Program Grant Award','2004-09-06 18:36:25','LPEF helps provide much needed student counseling for both Loma Prieta and CT English students.','This is the fourth year that LPEF has helped fund student counseling.\n<A HREF=\"http://www.lpef.org/local/2004-05 Counseling.pdf\">Counseling Program Award</a>',0,72,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (42,'lydia','CT Elective Classes Saved by LPEF Grant','2004-09-06 18:38:36','At the request of the District, LPEF awarded a $40,000 program grant in the Spring of 2003 in order to retain current CT English teachers and offer additional elective offerings at the middle school.','This LPEF grant helped make possible the addition of zero period classes and new elective offerings for 7th and 8th grade students.\n<a href=\"http://www.lpef.org/local/CT Electives 04-05.pdf\">CT Electives Program Award</a>',0,73,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (43,'lydia','Loma Prieta Computer Lab Upgraded','2004-09-06 18:41:30','Thanks to a LPEF program grant, all classes at Loma will now be able to utilize the computer lab with enough standardized computers equipped with the same software. ','Additionally, this technology grant will help all teachers better communicate and prepare by the purchase of district-wide software licenses.  \n<a href=\"http://www.lpef.org/local/computer upgrades 04-05.pdf\">Computer Upgrade Program Award</a>',0,422,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (44,'lydia','One Enchanted Evening Sets a New Record','2004-10-10 15:53:01','Combine a sell-out crowd with the efforts of 200 parent and student volunteers, along with the generosity of 300 donors who contributed 400 auction items and you have one truly enchanted evening!','The LPEF Gala held on Oct. 2nd netted $52,000 for critical programs for Loma Prieta and CT English schools. The event, held at Maison du Lac, featured wine tasting, music by the South Bay Stompers, silent auctions and finished with a wonderful dinner, spirited bidding on 5 live auctions, many sponsored by local realtors, and dancing to the music of the Lou DeLuca Band.  Revelers bid on items ranging from student class projects to stunning pieces of art and jewelry, merchandise and wine. \n\nThanks to sustained extraordinary community support, LPEF has granted over $195,000 in Program Awards to the District since we were founded in 2001. Children in our schools have benefited from programs in math, literacy, after-school enrichment, student counseling and library services funded by LPEF. Last year alone, we raised $95,000; and over 96% of those funds were available for grants. LPEF conducts two major fundraising efforts, the annual Gala and a community pledge drive. Preliminary contributions to the pledge drive are $40,000, which means LPEF is very close to meeting its annual goal. If you would like to make a donation, please visit www.lpef.org for a donation form.\n\nIn 2001 we knew the need for LPEF existed, and we hoped that we could engage the school administration, teachers and parents in a dialog about critical funding. Frankly, our dream was that we could establish LPEF as a support system for our tiny school district, build a track record that would instill confidence in our organization and, finally, be ready to help ensure strong local public schools remained here on the mountain. We knew we could not expect anyone in Sacramento or Washington to help our district match programs and services found in neighboring districts. We knew that our community would need to step up to help our children receive the most excellent education available.\n\nFour years later we say from the bottoms of our hearts: THANK YOU to everyone who has helped make our vision a reality. One Enchanted Evening was a smashing success because of the goodness of people. Parents. Neighbors. Friends. Relatives. Merchants. People who have reason to care about our kids and people who have no reason to care other than a commitment to education. We have strived to build trust and confidence in LPEF that money given will be accounted for. \n\nAt the Districts request, LPEF has committed over $100,000 in new grants for the 2004-2005 school year. By awarding early, LPEF helped the District retain all C.T. English teachers and save elective offerings at the middle school. Additionally, LPEF has committed to partial financial support for the Reading Recovery Program, student counseling and technology upgrades. We are currently talking with the district about other critical funding needs for programs designed to support student achievement.\n ',0,79,2,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
INSERT INTO `lpef_stories` VALUES (45,'lydia','Where Does the Money Go?','2004-10-10 15:58:54','At the Districts request, LPEF has committed over $100,000 in new grants for the 2004-2005 school year.','By awarding early, LPEF helped the District retain all C.T. English teachers and save elective offerings at the middle school. Additionally, LPEF has committed to partial financial support for the Reading Recovery Program, student counseling and technology upgrades. \n\nFundraising is a never-ending challenge.  The magnitude of time, energy and effort to produce the Gala is enormous.  Over 200 parents and community members volunteered time to help produce this event, well over 300 donors contributed 400 items to the auction and 375 attendees make this sold out event truly an evening to remember. All this for a district with less than 600 students.\n\nWe need to do more! Superintendent Henry Castaniada, Principal Diana Hallock, and teachers have asked LPEF to fix a critical technology problem and provide funding for after-school enrichment at C.T. and Loma.\n\nWe appreciate every donation whether it is time, money or an item for the auction.  We are especially grateful to Patti and Bill Hughes for the use of their lovely gardens. The gifts of time and classroom projects created by teachers, room parents and students are indeed treasures. We could not hold the Gala without the support of parents, community members and merchants.\n\nYou might ask, Why do all those people do it?  As volunteers of LPEF we ask ourselves this question often.  And from August 1st until October 15th we ask it hourly!  We can assure you no one volunteers because they enjoy asking friends, neighbors and merchants for money and donations.  So, why?  We believe in our children.  We want their futures to be filled with dreams and aspirationsfor themselves and for others.  We volunteer because we have tremendous trust in our teachers and administrators.  And we have unwavering faith that our community will continue to support us in this mission.\n ',0,1180,6,'lydia','','2099-12-31 23:59:59','0');
